questiontext.text: If the probability that you will pass this test is \( 0.84 \), find the probability that you will not pass this test.
Which of the following is not a valid probability distribution?
Find the mean of the probability distribution below.
Find the (population) standard deviation of the probability distribution below.

The number of fire calls the Conestoga Valley Fire Company receives per day is distributed as follows:

Find the expected number of calls per day.
A fair eight-sided die is rolled 10 times. Find the probability that exactly 4 8's are rolled.
About 80% of all applicants are able to pass a driver's proficiency road test. If 15 people take the test, find the probability that more than 10 of them will pass the test.
A history class has 75 members. If there is a 12% absentee rate per class meeting, find the variance of the number of students who will be absent from each class.
Find the area under the standard normal distribution curve between \( z = -0.81 \) and \( z = 1.28 \).
Find \( P(z > -2.06) \). Use the standard normal distribution.
Find \( P(z < 0.05) \). Use the standard normal distribution.

In a federal prison, inmates can select to complete high school, take college courses, or do neither. The following survey results were obtained using ages of the inmates.

If a prisoner is selected at random, find the probability that the prisoner is 30 or older, or taking high school courses.

The average height of a certain age group of people is 53 inches. The standard deviation is 4 inches. If the variable is normally distributed, find the probability that a randomly selected individual's height is less than 50 inches.

The average number of gallons of sports drink consumed by the football team during a game is 20, with a standard deviation of 3 gallons. Assume the variable is normally distributed. When a game is played, find the probability that more than 23 gallons of sports drink are consumed?

The average amount of rainfall in Greenville is 49 inches. The standard deviation is 8 inches. Find the probability that Greenville will receive between 45 and 56 inches of rain in a given year. Assume a normal distribution.
A single card is selected at random from a standard 52-card deck. Find the probability that the card is a face card or a club.

Twenty-five percent of all deaths (all ages) are caused by diseases of the heart. Ischemic heart disease accounts for 16.4% of all deaths and heart failure for 2.3%. Choose one death at random. Find the probability that it is from ischemic heart disease, given that it was from heart disease.
Two cards are drawn from a standard 52-card deck without replacement. Find the probability that neither is a 5.

A fast-food restaurant offers a "4 for 5" meal special. The choices are:

  • Sandwiches: Grilled Chicken, Hamburger, Turkey Burger, or Pork Chop
  • Sides: French Fries, Baked Beans, Mac and Cheese
  • Dessert: Cherry Cheesecake, Apple Pie, Fried Twinkie, Chocolate Cake, Snickerdoodle Cookie
  • Drink: Pepsi, Diet Pepsi, Dr. Pepper, Mountain Dew, Lemonade, Water

How many different combinations are possible if the customer must choose a sandwich, a side, a dessert, and a drink?
At the state track meet, 12 relay teams make finals in the 4x800 meter relay. If the top 9 teams earn medals, how many different sets of medalists are possible?
The Foreign Language Club is showing a four-movie marathon of subtitled movies. How many ways can they choose 4 from the 11 available?
A drawer contains 11 identical red socks and 8 identical black socks. Suppose that you choose two socks at random in the dark. Find the probability that you get a pair of red socks.

The average composite score on the ACT in a given school district is 20.8, with a standard deviation of 5.8. The bottom 5% of the student body is required to attend ACT prep sessions during study hall. What is the minimum score required in order to avoid having to attend the ACT prep sessions? Your answer should be a whole number.

feedback.text: Careful! A score of 11 would actually fall in the bottom 5%. Remember, we always round up when finding a minimum cutoff score.

questiontext.text: Membership in an elite organization requires a test score in the top 30% range. If \( \mu = 115 \) and \( \sigma^2 = 144 \), find the lowest acceptable score that would enable a candidate to apply for membership. Assume the variable is normally distributed. Your answer should be a whole number.

feedback.text: Careful! A score of 121 would not be in the top 30%. Remember to round up when finding a minimum cutoff score.

questiontext.text: The average electric bill in a residential area is $72 for the month of April. The standard deviation is $6. If the amounts of the electric bills are normally distributed, find the probability that the mean of the bills for 15 residents will be less than $75. Round your answer to four decimal places.

feedback.text: Correct answer using calculator: \( 0.9735963136 \approx 0.9736 \). A little bit of tolerance has been added.
Correct answer using the z table: 0.9738. A little bit of tolerance has been added.
